## Loop safety & edge cases (no infinite loops)

The 5-iteration cap is the primary guard. These rules close the remaining edge cases so a loop can never spin forever or stall silently:

- **Notify, don't halt (default).** When a loop gives up (cap reached, deadlock, or no-progress), the **anti-infinite-loop cap still stops that loop**, but the **pipeline keeps going by default**. Mark the stage `needs-attention`, copy the open findings into `actionRequired`/`blockers` as **notifications** (surfaced on the local **and** fleet dashboards), and move to the next stage **wherever technically possible**. Only set `phase: "blocked"` and stop when continuing is genuinely impossible — a hard technical dependency (e.g. backend won't build, so tests can't run). Unresolved items always land in the final production report.
- **Exact-phrase only.** A loop advances **only** when `lastVerdict` equals the stage's exit phrase character-for-character. Near-misses (missing period, extra words, different casing) do **not** advance — instruct every verify agent to emit the exact phrase on its own line. When in doubt, treat as "not satisfied".
- **Deadlock guard (not satisfied + no findings).** If a verify agent does **not** emit the exit phrase but returns an **empty findings table**, do **not** launch the fix agent (it would have no work and loop uselessly). Mark the stage `needs-attention` with notification `"verify not satisfied but produced no actionable findings"` and continue (escalate/stop only if it gates a hard dependency).
- **No-progress / oscillation guard.** Maya compares each new verify report to the previous one. If two **consecutive** fix→verify cycles show **no net reduction** in open findings (same or higher count, or the identical finding IDs persist), stop that loop early (even below 5), mark the stage `needs-attention` with notification `"no progress across 2 cycles"`, and continue. This catches fix-A-breaks-B oscillation without halting the run.
- **Counter-integrity backstop.** Sunny independently counts how many times it has launched each verify agent this stage. If Maya's `state.json` counter ever disagrees or fails to increment, Sunny uses its own count and still enforces the cap — a stuck counter can never disable the cap.
- **Cap is checked before re-fixing.** Always read `state.json` and evaluate `>= maxIterations` **before** launching the fix agent again, never after.
- **Generators run once.** In the per-layer test stages the unit/integration/functional **generators run once**; only the per-layer fix agents run inside the loops. Never re-enter generation from a verify failure.
- **Genuinely-blocked fix.** A fix agent that cannot resolve a finding must say so explicitly ("No — {blockers}"); Sunny stops re-looping that item, records it as a `needs-attention` notification, and continues (only hard-stopping if it gates a hard dependency).
- **Fresh run resets counters.** On a brand-new intake Maya resets all counters to 0; mid-run, counters are never reset (so a stage cannot dodge its cap by restarting).

## Task launch template

Every Task prompt must include:

```
Full Repository Path: {absolute workspace path}
Context files (read before acting):
- .sunny/context/project-context.md
- .sunny/context/state.json
- {other relevant files}

Handoff from Context Agent:
{trimmed handoff block}

Your task: {specific phase instructions}

On completion: return structured output for Context Agent persistence.
Do NOT write to .sunny/context/ yourself — Context Agent owns the store.
If you changed code/config: run `graphify update <project-root>` before returning (readonly agents: query graphify only, do not update).
```

## User communication

- Announce phase transitions: "Sunny: Starting backend verification (iteration 2/5)..."
- On loop exit: quote the exact verdict line.
- On needs-attention: note the stage was capped/deferred, surface the items as notifications (they appear on the local + fleet dashboards), and continue — do not halt.
- On blocked (hard dependency only): list blockers from `state.json` and ask the user how to proceed.
- On complete: deliver run guide, architecture diagram summary, links to key files, and any outstanding `needs-attention`/`actionRequired` items.

## Do not

- Skip context-agent between agent runs.
- Accept partial verdicts — the exit phrases must match exactly.
- Generate monolithic JHipster apps.
- Allow mock/fake data in the backend.
- Stop before production-standards-agent runs only when a **hard technical dependency** makes continuing impossible (default: keep going and collect outstanding items in the final report).
